        'Magwitch\'s bleak summary of his life is devastating in its simplicity. The rhythmic repetition — "in jail and out of jail" — mimics the cyclical trap of poverty and crime. There is no middle ground, no stable period of honest living; Magwitch\'s life alternates mechanically between incarceration and brief, precarious freedom. The phrase exposes the failure of the Victorian penal system to rehabilitate or reform — it merely cycles people through punishment without addressing the underlying conditions that produce crime. The casual "pretty much" adds a note of resigned acceptance that makes the statement even more powerful. Magwitch does not rage against injustice; he simply states facts. This matter-of-fact tone is more damning than any polemic.',
