        'Miss Havisham\'s anguished cry marks her moral awakening — the moment she recognises the full extent of the suffering she has caused. The repetition suggests she is asking the question again and again, unable to absorb the enormity of the answer. The simplicity of the language — just six common words — contrasts with her previous elaborate speeches about love and revenge. Stripped of rhetoric, Miss Havisham confronts her actions in their bare reality. The question is not rhetorical but genuine: she truly does not understand how she became capable of such cruelty, because her decades of bitterness have numbed her moral sense. This cry begins her journey toward repentance, which will culminate in the fire that consumes her — a symbolic purging of the bitterness that has defined her life.',
